00:47:49.516 --> 00:47:50.278
[LAUGHTER]

00:47:50.278 --> 00:47:51.486
AUDIENCE: Translators, maybe.

00:47:51.486 --> 00:47:52.852
But I don't think interpreters.

00:47:52.852 --> 00:47:54.435
NATALY KELLY: That's
what a lot people

00:47:54.435 --> 00:47:56.630
say because of the
complexity of speech.

00:47:56.630 --> 00:48:00.340
And text as much
easier to automate.

00:48:00.340 --> 00:48:02.525
There are a few types
of machine translation.

00:48:02.525 --> 00:48:05.780
Google Translate is called
statistical machine translation

00:48:05.780 --> 00:48:08.050
based on lots of data.

00:48:08.050 --> 00:48:10.900
And there's is also something
called rules-based machine

00:48:10.900 --> 00:48:14.010
translation, in which basically
you write the rules in detail

00:48:14.010 --> 00:48:19.590
for who to treat different
verbs, subject-verb agreements,

00:48:19.590 --> 00:48:22.006
gender, all of the
those kinds of things.

00:48:22.006 --> 00:48:23.872
And then there's
a hybrid approach

00:48:23.872 --> 00:48:24.830
to machine translation.

00:48:24.830 --> 00:48:26.980
And there are a lot of
efforts to automate speech,

00:48:26.980 --> 00:48:29.470
and in fact Google has
been involved in some.

00:48:29.470 --> 00:48:31.126
And some of them
are quite successful

00:48:31.126 --> 00:48:35.120
but for very limited domains
and for very specific language

00:48:35.120 --> 00:48:36.070
pairs.

00:48:36.070 --> 00:48:39.600
And also this whole thing
about speaking comprehension,

00:48:39.600 --> 00:48:42.470
these different abilities,
look at computers.

00:48:42.470 --> 00:48:46.890
Computers can usually
produce spoken language

00:48:46.890 --> 00:48:49.520
much more easily than they
can comprehend because

00:48:49.520 --> 00:48:52.590
of all the different variations
in people's speech patterns.

00:48:52.590 --> 00:48:54.674
And that might be why you
see some people evaluate

00:48:54.674 --> 00:48:56.298
their listening and
their comprehension

00:48:56.298 --> 00:48:58.490
lower than their speech
because in some cases

00:48:58.490 --> 00:48:59.900
it can be quite hard.

00:48:59.900 --> 00:49:02.240
There's a lot of
individual variation.

00:49:02.240 --> 00:49:06.690
So the future of translator,
I think, is quite bright.

00:49:06.690 --> 00:49:08.970
I follow the market
as a researcher.

00:49:08.970 --> 00:49:11.390
And the language services
market for translation

00:49:11.390 --> 00:49:14.630
and interpreting has been
growing at double digit growth

00:49:14.630 --> 00:49:20.080
rates, compound annual growth
rates, for the last 10 years.

00:49:20.080 --> 00:49:24.210
And as more people getting
access to information,

00:49:24.210 --> 00:49:26.970
translation is
becoming more and more

00:49:26.970 --> 00:49:29.520
and in the translation
community, a lot of people

00:49:29.520 --> 00:49:31.780
absolutely hate
Google Translate,

00:49:31.780 --> 00:49:35.430
because they think it leads
to really poor translations

00:49:35.430 --> 00:49:37.090
that a human could
have done better.

00:49:37.090 --> 00:49:39.830
And so they absolutely
cannot stand Google Translate

00:49:39.830 --> 00:49:43.022
because of the impact that they
see and people thinking, oh,

00:49:43.022 --> 00:49:43.980
well, that's just easy.

00:49:43.980 --> 00:49:46.202
You just drop it in
Google Translate.

00:49:46.202 --> 00:49:48.160
But I think that
Google Translate

00:49:48.160 --> 00:49:49.960
and other such free
services are actually

00:49:49.960 --> 00:49:53.150
creating a bigger
market for translation

00:49:53.150 --> 00:49:56.920
because it's increasing the
awareness of, oh, it maybe

00:49:56.920 --> 00:49:58.570
doesn't have to be so hard.

00:49:58.570 --> 00:50:01.560
So what's happening is a lot
of people are using that.

00:50:01.560 --> 00:50:03.590
Maybe they put the content
up on their website.

00:50:03.590 --> 00:50:06.850
Customers can find them
because of SEO increases.

00:50:06.850 --> 00:50:09.010
But then, suddenly,
customers are complaining,

00:50:09.010 --> 00:50:10.120
oh, you have a
mistranslation here.

00:50:10.120 --> 00:50:11.119
This doesn't make sense.

00:50:11.119 --> 00:50:14.650
So then they're actually paying
for professional post editing

00:50:14.650 --> 00:50:16.500
is what it's called,
a human translator

00:50:16.500 --> 00:50:19.090
cleans up the machine
translation output.

00:50:19.090 --> 00:50:21.530
Or they're simply
paying a human to do it.

00:50:21.530 --> 00:50:23.360
So that actually
writing awareness,

00:50:23.360 --> 00:50:27.730
driving market demand, for
professional human services.

00:50:27.730 --> 00:50:32.190
And Ray Kurzweil agreed with me.

00:50:32.190 --> 00:50:35.850
He believes that
there is definitely

00:50:35.850 --> 00:50:39.120
a point where machine
translation of text

00:50:39.120 --> 00:50:42.170
will equal human output,
because, remember,

00:50:42.170 --> 00:50:45.680
human output isn't
perfect either.

00:50:45.680 --> 00:50:48.490
And a lot that is
very subjective.

00:50:48.490 --> 00:50:51.140
But he does believe that
simultaneous interpretation

00:50:51.140 --> 00:50:55.990
of speech across languages
will probably not

00:50:55.990 --> 00:50:58.440
reach what humans can do.

00:50:58.440 --> 00:51:02.344
So that's an assessment
in the future.

00:51:02.344 --> 00:51:03.760
MICHAEL ERARD: I
think what's cool

00:51:03.760 --> 00:51:08.625
listening to you talk about
the future of translators

00:51:08.625 --> 00:51:13.950
an translators is that there are
really no cliches or platitudes

00:51:13.950 --> 00:51:17.610
that you touch on or have
to use to promise a future.

00:51:17.610 --> 00:51:20.990
But I think if you talk about
the future of hyperpolyglots,

00:51:20.990 --> 00:51:24.425
you have to talk about the
world shrinking and access

00:51:24.425 --> 00:51:27.820
to information--
lots of cliches.

00:51:27.820 --> 00:51:31.620
I think it's a similarly
bright sort of future,

00:51:31.620 --> 00:51:36.520
to the degree that people
have better access and faster

00:51:36.520 --> 00:51:42.090
access to language resources
and to native speakers online.

00:51:42.090 --> 00:51:46.048
So you can actually do
more without getting up.

00:51:46.048 --> 00:51:50.570
And I think also the kinds
of organizational and

00:51:50.570 --> 00:51:54.850
institutional environments
that use and develop

00:51:54.850 --> 00:52:00.070
the hyperpolyglots neurology
are increasing as well.

00:52:00.070 --> 00:52:05.310
So those people who might have
that aptitude who would just

00:52:05.310 --> 00:52:07.180
be out there and never
get the opportunity

00:52:07.180 --> 00:52:12.070
are actually going to
have to that increasingly.

00:52:12.070 --> 00:52:13.530
On the flip side
of that, though,

00:52:13.530 --> 00:52:17.210
is the thing that came earlier
was the degree to which

00:52:17.210 --> 00:52:20.530
interest in programming
languages soaks up---

00:52:20.530 --> 00:52:24.880
and it would be interesting
to talk about why programming

00:52:24.880 --> 00:52:27.590
languages are more attractive
than human languages.

00:52:27.590 --> 00:52:32.880
And I think the boundedness
and the discrete of one

00:52:32.880 --> 00:52:35.959
versus the other
is-- and we could

00:52:35.959 --> 00:52:41.240
talk about that-- is definitely
what makes one more attractive.

00:52:41.240 --> 00:52:41.740
Yes.

00:52:41.740 --> 00:52:44.090
AUDIENCE: Do many of
these hyperpolyglots

00:52:44.090 --> 00:52:45.030
make a living at it?

00:52:45.030 --> 00:52:48.320
Or is it an avocation?

00:52:48.320 --> 00:52:51.060
MICHAEL ERARD: Yeah, so one
of the slides that we skipped

00:52:51.060 --> 00:52:54.300
was where they work
or where do find them?

00:52:54.300 --> 00:52:57.080
And I split them
into two groups.

00:52:57.080 --> 00:52:59.710
There are
institutionalized ones--

00:52:59.710 --> 00:53:02.235
[LAUGHTER]

00:53:02.235 --> 00:53:04.130
--like Graham.

00:53:04.130 --> 00:53:07.630
So they work in an organization
that is multilingual,

00:53:07.630 --> 00:53:09.810
where being multilingual
and learning languages

00:53:09.810 --> 00:53:11.820
is an expected part of the job.

00:53:11.820 --> 00:53:15.120
He has two months
professional development

00:53:15.120 --> 00:53:17.620
to go to another
country to learn either

00:53:17.620 --> 00:53:20.358
on language that he has
or a language that he

00:53:20.358 --> 00:53:21.570
wants to learn.

00:53:21.570 --> 00:53:24.285
And he may never
actually ever translate

00:53:24.285 --> 00:53:25.500
with that language but--

00:53:25.500 --> 00:53:26.506
AUDIENCE: What
organization is he?

00:53:26.506 --> 00:53:28.130
MICHAEL ERARD: The
European Commission.

00:53:28.130 --> 00:53:29.420
AUDIENCE: Oh.

00:53:29.420 --> 00:53:31.260
MICHAEL ERARD: And
that's just expected.

00:53:31.260 --> 00:53:34.208
So he's not a dilettante.

00:53:34.208 --> 00:53:36.860
He's not considered
in that environment.

00:53:36.860 --> 00:53:41.430
And there are
people who are d, So

00:53:41.430 --> 00:53:46.030
the guy who did the shadowing,
that marching thing,

00:53:46.030 --> 00:53:49.840
when I met him he was
unemployed, doing translation

00:53:49.840 --> 00:53:52.210
in Korean.

00:53:52.210 --> 00:53:57.560
He's now employed as a
linguistics professor in Oman.

00:53:57.560 --> 00:53:58.970
A lot of them are academics.

00:53:58.970 --> 00:54:00.240
Some of them are translators.

00:54:00.240 --> 00:54:02.970
So one of the ways
in which is there's

00:54:02.970 --> 00:54:05.470
a certain amount of similarity
between the translators

00:54:05.470 --> 00:54:08.500
and the hyperpolyglots
is the hyperpolyglots,

00:54:08.500 --> 00:54:11.880
for exactly that sort
of reason, end up

00:54:11.880 --> 00:54:15.100
doing translation work of
various types-- translation

00:54:15.100 --> 00:54:17.910
work and not interpretation.

00:54:17.910 --> 00:54:21.886
I don't know that I met
anyone who is an interpreter.

00:54:21.886 --> 00:54:22.880
NATALY KELLY: Yeah.

00:54:22.880 --> 00:54:26.359
Translation if have enough
time and you're not--

00:54:26.359 --> 00:54:29.360
maybe if you're doing maybe
not on a professional level

00:54:29.360 --> 00:54:30.730
for all languages.

00:54:30.730 --> 00:54:34.280
A lot poets, for example,
will translate poetry

00:54:34.280 --> 00:54:37.103
because they can basically
find other translations,

00:54:37.103 --> 00:54:39.067
compare them, use a
dictionary, use resources.

00:54:39.067 --> 00:54:41.522
They have the luxury of time
to really research things

00:54:41.522 --> 00:54:44.959
and understand them thoroughly
and introduce a translation.

00:54:44.959 --> 00:54:46.432
So it is possible.

00:54:46.432 --> 00:54:48.396
Most professional
translators, however,

00:54:48.396 --> 00:54:52.530
don't have that luxury because
they to reach a certain number

00:54:52.530 --> 00:54:57.132
words per hour in
order to make a living.

00:54:57.132 --> 00:55:00.590
AUDIENCE: How many
words per hour is that?

00:55:00.590 --> 00:55:04.032
MICHAEL ERARD: Well the average
is about 2,500 words per day.

00:55:04.032 --> 00:55:05.406
And that hasn't
changed much even

00:55:05.406 --> 00:55:08.030
with computer assisted
translation tools and machine

00:55:08.030 --> 00:55:10.490
translation tools
that they're using.

00:55:10.490 --> 00:55:11.950
AUDIENCE: Has the
accuracy gone up,

00:55:11.950 --> 00:55:14.248
like is that metric
that's measured, right?

00:55:14.248 --> 00:55:15.987
NATALY KELLY: You
know there is lack

00:55:15.987 --> 00:55:18.070
of measurement of
these types of things.

00:55:18.070 --> 00:55:20.480
The market is very
fragmented, so there

00:55:20.480 --> 00:55:22.646
aren't a lot of good studies
out there to show that.

00:55:22.646 --> 00:55:25.051
But one of the
benefits of using tools

00:55:25.051 --> 00:55:26.975
is precisely accuracy
and consistency

00:55:26.975 --> 00:55:30.750
of terminology, which is
really important, especially

00:55:30.750 --> 00:55:34.619
when you've got your [INAUDIBLE]
guidelines that differ from one

00:55:34.619 --> 00:55:36.035
company to another,
companies that

00:55:36.035 --> 00:55:37.750
create their own terminology.

00:55:37.750 --> 00:55:40.690
And we have a lot of
examples in the book

00:55:40.690 --> 00:55:42.650
of this kind of
thing-- translators

00:55:42.650 --> 00:55:44.913
for Harlequin romance
novels, interpreters

00:55:44.913 --> 00:55:48.845
who interpret for
astronauts, interpreters

00:55:48.845 --> 00:55:51.243
who interpret for celebrities.

00:55:51.243 --> 00:55:53.170
And translators and
interpreters work in

00:55:53.170 --> 00:55:55.620
just so many different
technical areas

00:55:55.620 --> 00:55:59.280
that that is an
ongoing challenge

00:55:59.280 --> 00:56:02.680
to make sure they have
consistent terminology

00:56:02.680 --> 00:56:05.640
and using other sources to make
sure they're, whatever they're

00:56:05.640 --> 00:56:08.896
producing, is in alignment
with other information that's

00:56:08.896 --> 00:56:09.396
out there.

00:56:09.396 --> 00:56:10.872
AUDIENCE: How do they, like,
feed this back somewhere?

00:56:10.872 --> 00:56:13.004
Because that's
the important part

00:56:13.004 --> 00:56:15.300
to improving computer
aided translated, right?

00:56:15.300 --> 00:56:16.290
NATALY KELLY: Yes.

00:56:16.290 --> 00:56:17.070
This is the thing.

00:56:17.070 --> 00:56:19.383
So most of the files
that they're creating

00:56:19.383 --> 00:56:21.070
are called translation
memory files,

00:56:21.070 --> 00:56:23.480
so it's basically a
database of translation.

00:56:23.480 --> 00:56:26.657
So they have a column
with the source language

00:56:26.657 --> 00:56:28.240
and a column with
the target language.

00:56:28.240 --> 00:56:30.030
So the tools that
they use will show

00:56:30.030 --> 00:56:32.540
them a fuzzy match
or a perfect match.

00:56:32.540 --> 00:56:34.995
It will show, oh,
98% of this segment

00:56:34.995 --> 00:56:36.995
looks like something that
you translated before.

00:56:36.995 --> 00:56:38.960
And it will pop up
and will show that.

00:56:38.960 --> 00:56:41.420
And then they can just
simply correct or tweak it

00:56:41.420 --> 00:56:43.260
to make it perfect.

00:56:43.260 --> 00:56:46.864
So translators amass these
transition memory files.

00:56:46.864 --> 00:56:49.435
Sometimes they delver
them back to the client.

00:56:49.435 --> 00:56:51.280
Sometimes they don't.

00:56:51.280 --> 00:56:54.720
So there's all this data
--I know you guys can see

00:56:54.720 --> 00:56:55.690
the problem with this--

00:56:55.690 --> 00:56:56.930
[LAUGHTER]

00:56:56.930 --> 00:56:59.705
that isn't being
shared with anyone

00:56:59.705 --> 00:57:02.750
and is being stored, usually,
on individual personal computers

00:57:02.750 --> 00:57:04.660
in people's homes.

00:57:04.660 --> 00:57:07.180
And Google actually has
something called the translator

00:57:07.180 --> 00:57:10.406
toolkit, which is
designed to help people

00:57:10.406 --> 00:57:13.610
be able to store
this and leverage it.

00:57:13.610 --> 00:57:16.060
But there are
entrenched providers

00:57:16.060 --> 00:57:18.510
that have been
there for decades.

00:57:18.510 --> 00:57:21.980
And they tend to use those
tools that are installed locally

00:57:21.980 --> 00:57:24.222
on their local computer.

00:57:24.222 --> 00:57:27.771
So there is a tendency to
move things toward the cloud.

00:57:27.771 --> 00:57:29.610
And I think then we
can harvest that.

00:57:29.610 --> 00:57:30.350
Information.

00:57:30.350 --> 00:57:32.510
But let's not forget--
one of the other reasons

00:57:32.510 --> 00:57:35.370
that people like to preserve
that information is because

00:57:35.370 --> 00:57:37.316
of confidentiality in
the a lot of the stuff

00:57:37.316 --> 00:57:38.410
that they're translating.

00:57:38.410 --> 00:57:42.240
So there is this debate of how
much should go to the cloud

00:57:42.240 --> 00:57:44.700
And how much do we we
want to keep secure.

00:57:44.700 --> 00:57:46.969
And there's a lot of
discussion about that.

00:57:46.969 --> 00:57:48.677
AUDIENCE: That would
be a really cool way

00:57:48.677 --> 00:57:49.907
to leak a nuclear secret.

00:57:49.907 --> 00:57:52.180
It's like a big secret--
oh, it turns out

00:57:52.180 --> 00:57:53.980
we have a translation
for all things

00:57:53.980 --> 00:57:55.296
nuclear between [INAUDIBLE].

00:57:55.296 --> 00:57:56.784
[LAUGHTER]

00:57:56.784 --> 00:57:58.344
NATALY KELLY: Oh and believe me.

00:57:58.344 --> 00:58:00.260
There are lots of
interpreters and translators

00:58:00.260 --> 00:58:02.710
who are doing that work.

00:58:02.710 --> 00:58:05.080
I used to get
recorded transcripts

00:58:05.080 --> 00:58:06.810
from intelligence agencies.

00:58:06.810 --> 00:58:08.492
Or I would get the
recordings, and I

00:58:08.492 --> 00:58:09.465
would have to create
the transcripts.

00:58:09.465 --> 00:58:11.700
So this is another variant
that I didn't put there,

00:58:11.700 --> 00:58:13.660
where you're listening
and you're transcribing

00:58:13.660 --> 00:58:15.366
and you're translating
at the same time.

00:58:15.366 --> 00:58:16.990
So and I would hear
all kind of things.

00:58:16.990 --> 00:58:18.656
Of course, I didn't
have the big picture

00:58:18.656 --> 00:58:22.510
to know what this was
related to-- if you

00:58:22.510 --> 00:58:24.090
would harness all
that information.

00:58:24.090 --> 00:58:26.370
And the CIA,
intelligence agencies,

00:58:26.370 --> 00:58:28.358
have had a really hard
problem with this.

00:58:28.358 --> 00:58:29.849
They haven't been able to
recruit enough translators

00:58:29.849 --> 00:58:32.085
and interpreters, especially
for critical languages

00:58:32.085 --> 00:58:35.090
like [INAUDIBLE] and Pashto--
and even Arabic, which

00:58:35.090 --> 00:58:37.130
is a pretty widely
spoken language.

00:58:37.130 --> 00:58:39.970
But not everybody
wants to do that work.

00:58:39.970 --> 00:58:42.880
So yeah.

